==Latin==
In Latin, the letter written as V in ancient times represented either a [[vowel]] or a [[consonant]] depending on its position and the word.  These two forms had distinct [[pronunciation]]s and different [[metre|metrical]] treatment in [[poetry]].

A modern [[typography|typographical]] convention is to write [[U]] for the vowel and leave V as the consonant.  Generally speaking [[dictionary|dictionaries]] always write U this way and the majority of reprints of classical texts adapt them and show U too.  The use of V for the vowel in new works is usually a deliberately [[classical]] style or appearance, and that includes for example in [[inscription]]s on new [[monument]]s and the like.

===Pronunciation===
As consonant,
* Classical: IPA: /w/
As vowel,
* Classical: IPA: short /u/, long /u:/

